<rss version="2.0"><channel><title>守护者</title><description>卫报全文RSS。获取更多全文RSS：https://feedx.net</description><link/> https://theguardian.com <item><title><![CDATA[Japan to release second batch of wastewater from Fukushima nuclear plant next week]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/29/japan-fukushima-nuclear-powerplant-wastewater-release-second-batch]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-29T03:21:04Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/81bed9823fef1823449e17c9620a20e9925ee3d4/0_511_5202_3123 /master/5202.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=4ea450ac4b53cfdeb5f68aac2b4b67a6&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;8 月 31 日，日本福岛县相马市 Hamanoeki 鱼市场和美食广场上当地捕获的海鲜2023 年。 &lt;/div>;&lt;p>;日本将从下周开始释放受损福岛核电站的第二批废水，该核电站运营商表示，此举&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com /environment/2023/aug/28/japan-businesses-abusive-phone-calls-china-fukushima-waste-water&quot;>;8月份开始时激怒了中国和其他国家&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;关于8 月 24 日，日本开始向太平洋排放自 2011 年海啸摧毁该设施以来收集的 134 万吨废水中的一部分。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“第一次排放后的检查已经完成……（第二次） ）将于 10 月 5 日开始放电，”东京电力 (Tepco) 周四表示。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;中国 &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/24/ japan-begins-release-fukushima-wastewater-into-pacific-ocean&quot;>;在首次释放后禁止所有日本海鲜进口&lt;/a>;，释放活动于 9 月 11 日结束，尽管东京方面坚称该行动不会带来任何风险。&lt;/p >; &lt;p>;据报道，与日本关系也很冷淡的俄罗斯正在考虑效仿海鲜禁令。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https: //www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/25/china-drastically-cuts-seafood-imports-from-japan-in-wake-of-fukushima-water-release&quot;>;中国大幅削减从日本进口海鲜福岛核电站泄水后&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;第一阶段计划向太平洋泄水 134 万吨，相当于 500 多吨，其中约 7,800 吨奥运会游泳池。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;东京电力表示，水中除氚外的所有放射性元素均已过滤，处于安全水平之内。这一观点得到了联合国原子能机构的支持。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;中国指责日本将海洋当作“下水道”使用，所罗门群岛总理马纳西·索加瓦雷上周在联合国也提出了同样的指控，&lt;a href =&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/jul/17/china-to-fill-the-gap-in-solomon-islands-budget-as-pm-blasts-unneighbourly-australia-and-我们&quot;>;与北京发展了密切关系&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;此次释放预计需要数十年时间才能完成，旨在腾出空间，最终开始清除高度危险的放射性燃料和瓦砾来自失事反应堆。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“与第一次排放的情况一样，我们将继续监测氚含量。我们将继续以科学证据为基础，以易于理解的方式告知公众。”东京电力官员小野彰周四对记者表示。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;尽管中国禁止进口日本海鲜，但据报道，中国船只仍在继续捕捞日本海鲜。 &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;美国驻日本大使拉姆·伊曼纽尔 (Rahm Emanuel) 上周发布了他所说的 9 月 15 日在日本附近的中国渔船的照片。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“他们说一张图片胜过一千个文字。 9 月 15 日，中国对同一海域实施海鲜禁运后，中国船只在日本沿海捕鱼。”伊曼纽尔在社交媒体平台 X 上表示。&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 29 Sep 2023 11:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Evergrande founder ‘being investigated for suspected crimes’]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2023/sep/28/evergrande-founder-being-investigated-for-suspected-crimes]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-28T18:08:23Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/510c4b32627a08c062defd0eac8af464cc13e3cb/0_133_4000_2400 /master/4000.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=2826c96e72018d2c6a7bbf1dcb3fe6d5&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;西装男&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;中国恒大创始人因涉嫌“违法犯罪”正在接受调查该集团表示，随着债权人越来越担心这家全球负债最重的房地产开发商的前景。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;恒大集团的总负债超过 3000 亿美元（2450 亿英镑），但没有透露是否许家印仍在经营公司，或者他因什么罪行正在接受调查。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;该消息是在公司股票交易几小时后发布的 &lt;a href=&quot;https://www .theguardian.com/business/2023/sep/28/evergrande-halts-share-trading-as-woes-mount-for-china-property-giant&quot;>;因有报道称许已被安置而被暂停&lt;/a>; &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/27/chair-china-evergrande-reportedly-put-under-police-surveillance&quot;>;警方监视&lt;/a>;。恒大表示，该股将继续停牌，直至另行通知。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“公司特此公告，公司已接到有关部门通知，许家印先生……已被依法采取强制措施。”恒大表示，该消息首次表明，当局可能会追究这位亿万富翁创始人对开发商财务困境的责任，该财务困境已经席卷了房地产行业，该行业约占房地产行业的中国经济的四分之一。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;中国负债累累的房地产行业的动荡不断加深，有可能破坏北京方面为让陷入困境的经济重新站稳脚跟所做的努力，并引发投资者对疫情蔓延至中国经济的担忧。最新的事态发展对这家曾经最畅销的中国开发商来说是一个重大打击，自2021年现金紧缩公开并于2021年拖欠离岸债务以来，该开发商已陷入一场又一场危机。 &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;恒大一直在努力争取债权人批准其境外债务重组。本周，恒大表示，由于对其主要中国部门的调查，该公司无法发行新债，这一过程变得复杂。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;离岸债务重组计划现在看来将陷入困境，公司面临被一些分析师表示，清算金额正在上升。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;分析师表示，恒大的问题引发了中国当局进行干预的可能性，以应对对金融体系和更广泛经济可能产生的影响。&lt;/p>; &lt; “到目前为止，他们已经设法避免了防止由其中一名开发商引发的系统性危机的‘底线’，并且如果恒大的情况可能导致蔓延，几乎肯定会进一步干预，”副总裁克里斯托弗·贝多尔(Christopher Beddor)表示佳富龙洲经讯中国研究总监。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“但除此之外，他们的做法……常常显得矛盾，有时甚至语无伦次，这种情况一直持续到今天。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;中国媒体第一财经援引消息人士的话称，恒大的其他一些高管也正在接受调查。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;恒大没有立即回应路透社在亚洲营业时间以外的置评请求。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;恒大的最新困境是针对过去几周，北京推出了一系列措施，包括降低现有抵押贷款利率，以重振遭受重创的房地产行业。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;周四，财政部表示，中国将免除城市土地税用于从十月开始的经济适用房项目。该部表示，此类住房的买家和住房管理公司也将免征印花税。&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 29 Sep 2023 10:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Tesla trial begins over whether ‘experimental’ autopilot caused driver’s death]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/sep/28/tesla-lawsuite-autopilot-system-fatal-car-crash]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-29T02:04:17Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/aee7da13a367669c911a1e0d9c9a3886536eed72/0_296_3500_2100 /master/3500.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=39b3ccc0910262d846b9d1a275d58bc8&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;2020 年 7 月 23 日在莫斯科特斯拉 Model 3 电动汽车的内部。&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;代表特斯拉致命事故受害者的律师在周四加州审判的开庭陈述中指责该公司的自动驾驶驾驶员辅助系统，称“汽车公司永远不应该向消费者出售实验性车辆”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;该案源于一起民事诉讼，指控自动驾驶系统导致特斯拉 Model 3 车主米卡·李 (Micah Lee) 突然以 65 英里/小时（105 公里/小时）的速度冲出洛杉矶以东的高速公路，撞上一棵棕榈树并爆炸着火。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2022/nov/14/tesla-autopilot-landmark -case-man-v-machine&quot;>;涉及特斯拉自动驾驶仪的里程碑式审判权衡了“人还是机器”的过错&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;2019 年的事故导致 Lee 死亡，两名乘客重伤法庭文件显示，其中包括一名被开膛破肚的八岁男孩。该诉讼由乘客和李的遗产对特斯拉提起，指控特斯拉在出售汽车时知道自动驾驶仪和其他安全系统存在缺陷。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;原告律师乔纳森·迈克尔斯 (Jonathan Michaels) 在开场白中说道。加州河滨市审判中的声明称，37 岁的李在 2019 年以 6,000 美元的价格为他的 Model 3 购买了特斯拉的“全自动驾驶功能包”时，该系统还处于“测试版”状态，这意味着它还没有尚未准备好发布。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;迈克尔斯表示，该车的方向盘在高速公路上发生了 43 度的急转弯，并补充说“过度的转向指令是特斯拉的一个已知问题。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p >;特斯拉否认了这一说法，称其自动驾驶系统在高速行驶时在方向盘角度上设置了“护栏”，使其只能在高速公路上向左或向右稍微转向。它还为系统的安全性进行了辩护，并指责驾驶员醉酒。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“此案与自动驾驶仪无关，”特斯拉律师迈克尔·凯里 (Michael Carey) 表示。 “自动驾驶仪使道路更安全。这是一件好事，”他说。 “这是导致事故的典型人为错误。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这家电动汽车制造商还声称，尚不清楚事故发生时自动驾驶仪是否已启用。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;特斯拉已测试并推出其自动驾驶仪和更先进的全自动驾驶系统，埃隆·马斯克宣称这对其公司的未来至关重要，但已引起监管和法律审查。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;特斯拉在洛杉矶赢得了一场领先的审判今年 4 月，特斯拉发生了一起与其自动驾驶功能相关的事故，该公司的策略是告诉司机，尽管有“自动驾驶”的名字，但其技术需要人工监控。在 2019 年的那起事故中，一辆 Model S 突然转向路缘并导致驾驶员受伤。陪审员在判决后告诉路透社，他们认为特斯拉警告司机注意其系统，而司机分心是罪魁祸首。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;本周审判以及其他案件中的风险更高，因为死亡事件。特斯拉和原告律师在前期就双方可以提出哪些证据和论点展开了激烈的争论。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;例如，特斯拉赢得了排除马斯克有关自动驾驶仪的一些公开声明的竞标。然而，根据法庭文件，车祸受害者的律师可以辩称李的血液酒精含量低于法定限度。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;审判预计将持续几周。&lt;/p>;&lt;br>;&lt; hr>;&lt;div>;获取更多RSS：&lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.net&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.best&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.best&lt;/a>;&lt;br>;&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 29 Sep 2023 10:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Risk of miscalculation’ rises in South China Sea as Beijing ramps up aggressive tactics]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/29/risk-of-miscalculation-rises-in-south-china-sea-as-beijing-ramps-up-aggressive-tactics]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-29T01:57:18Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/5684ccb9c9525de02441960e4b779dcfcd99f1dc/0_10_1491_895 /master/1491.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=cf37f7ac00cec062935ccc1a5e3c548d&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;菲律宾海岸警卫队正在拆除南海黄岩岛附近设置的浮动屏障。&lt;/div>;&lt;在晃动的镜头中，可以看到菲律宾海岸警卫队的一名成员潜入南海水域，准备执行该国总统的指示。 “把它砍掉，”背景中的一个声音说道，海岸警卫队假扮成通气管中的渔民，开始砍断一根绳子。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这段视频于周一在附近拍摄。争议激烈的黄岩岛，表明菲律宾的使命是拆除中国海警设置的危险浮动屏障。菲律宾海岸警卫队声称，该设施的设立是为了切断菲律宾船只的通道，并指责其同行违反了国际法。中国为其行为辩称“专业且克制”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这一事件是南海争端不断加剧的最新一起——如果争端升级，&lt;a href=&quot;https: //www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/china-philippines-dispute-could-escalate-into-superpower-conflict-say-analysts&quot;>;可能会让菲律宾盟友美国与其发生对抗竞争对手中国&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;过去一年，马尼拉多次指责北京在南中国海采取危险和侵略性的策略，包括指控中国&lt;a href=&quot;https:// www.theguardian.com/world/2023/feb/15/philippines-president-summons-chinese-ambassador-over-laser-incident&quot;>;用军用级激光&lt;/a>;瞄准菲律宾船只，并且它&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/06/philippines-accuses-china-of-water-cannon-attack-in-spratly-islands&quot;>;瞄准水炮&lt;/a>;菲律宾船只在其国家专属经济区内航行。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“由于中国的升级，误算的风险越来越高，”菲律宾大学律师兼教授杰伊·L·巴通巴卡尔 (Jay L Batongbacal) 表示&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;北京否认其是侵略者的说法，并表示支持与菲律宾对话。上个月，中国外交部长王毅指责美国挑起北京和马尼拉之间的冲突，称其“破坏南海的和平与安宁，为美国自身的地缘政治战略服务”。&lt;/p >; &lt;h2>;努力摆脱“法律现实”&lt;/h2>; &lt;p>;南海争端长期存在且微妙。中国对几乎整个南海拥有主权，并坚称其对散布在该海域的珊瑚礁和岩石拥有历史性的主权声索——尽管联合国法庭认为这是没有法律依据的。中国&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jul/12/philippines-wins-south-china-sea-case-against-china&quot;>;多次公开拒绝海牙裁决&lt; /a>;.菲律宾以及越南、马来西亚、文莱和台湾也提出了相互竞争的主张。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-interactive=&quot;https://interactive.guim.co.uk/embed/iframe-wrapper/0.1/boot .js&quot; data-canonical-url=&quot;https://interactive.guim.co.uk/uploader/embed/2018/02/southchinasea-zip/giv-3902R1RZM3jdqmCh/&quot; data-alt=&quot;地图&quot;>; &lt;a href =&quot;https://interactive.guim.co.uk/uploader/embed/2018/02/southchinasea-zip/giv-3902R1RZM3jdqmCh/&quot;>;互动&lt;/a>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;Philippe Sands KC，演员作为2016年仲裁案的菲律宾律师，他表示该裁决是最终裁决。他说：“再多的政治、外交或经济努力也无法推翻这一法律现实。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;他补充说，“可以公平地得出结论，建立海洋地物的努力[例如黄岩岛附近的浮动屏障]，其主权存在争议，根据国际法是有问题的”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;美国不是南海争端的声索国，但认为该水域是南海的主要争议海域之一。世界上最繁忙的航线，对其国家利益至关重要。它还将菲律宾视为其在亚洲最古老的条约盟友。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;南海对菲律宾来说非常重要 - 这既是因为其丰富的鱼类供应，也因为其石油和天然气储量日益增加。马尼拉面临迫在眉睫的能源危机，这一点意义重大。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;036bbda03fcdd3abe79626ef03d9a018aa2ec183&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/036bbda03fcdd3abe79626ef03d9a018aa2ec183/0_95_3844_23 07/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;菲律宾渔民乘坐木船在中国控制的黄岩岛附近驶过一艘中国海警船。&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;600&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;菲律宾渔民乘坐木船在中国控制的黄岩岛附近驶过一艘中国海警船。&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;摄影：Ted Aljibe/法新社/Getty Images&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;分析人士表示，对于中国来说，海洋对于国内政治合法性、能源资源和战略重要性都具有重要意义，并且被认为是其国家战略的关键组成部分。防御。巴通巴卡尔表示，中国“渴望在其海岸线周围建立一个安全缓冲区”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;南海也被认为是中国海基核威慑的堡垒，高级研究员科林·科说新加坡南洋理工大学国防与战略研究所。他说，中国大部分弹道导弹核潜艇都驻扎在海南岛。 “中国将能够在这里对其潜在对手（例如美国和印度）投射我们所谓的二次打击能力。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;南海对北京来说非常重要，可以实现更广泛的防御Koh 补充道，原因如下。 “如果台湾问题发生冲突，南海是中国必须保卫的南侧。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;上个月，中国发布了一张新地图，其中有一条 10 段线，而不是典型的九段线，包括民主治理的台湾作为其领土的一部分。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;过去十年，中国通过建造和加固人工岛来加强其在南海的存在。 &lt;a href=&quot;https://apnews.com/article/business-china-beijing-xi-jinping-south-china-sea-d229070bc2373be1ca515390960a6e6c&quot;>;据美方称&lt;/a>;，这些设施已配备齐全，包括反舰和防空导弹系统、激光和干扰设备以及战斗机。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-interactive=&quot;https://interactive.guim.co.uk/embed/iframe-wrapper/0.1 /boot.js&quot; data-canonical-url=&quot;https://interactive.guim.co.uk/2018/08/interactive-now-and-then-embed/embed/embed.html?mobile_before=//i. guim.co.uk/img/media/7507d0a957ed127b97ee2b761ab698fcbe134bd5/0_0_7837_6379/master/7837.jpg----宽度=2000____质量=85____s=e0b899ecf3b90cfd92075c3b51fff5ef&amp;amp;桌面_之前=//i.guim.co.uk/img/media/7507d0a957ed127b97ee2b761ab698fcbe134bd5/0_0_7837_6379 /master/7837.jpg----width=1000____quality=85____s=b8d1226d4924d7f1876fa7a90d0b0fcc&amp;label_before=2015&amp;amp;mobile_after=//i.guim.co.uk/img/media/7f671d724c94249a4bf9768461c466d 121f93015/0_0_7837_6379/master/7837.jpg--- -width=2000____quality=85____s=1eb1d7cbe72368869026cfd9c8c1d133&amp;amp;desktop_after=//i.guim.co.uk/img/media/7f671d724c94249a4bf9768461c466d121f93015/0_0_7837_63 79/master/7837.jpg----width=1000____quality=85____s=e3942edc059d1eb35162717ae493713f&amp;label_after=2020&amp;amp; Analytics_label=Fiery%20Cross%20Reef%20part%20of%20the%20Spratly%20Islands%20group%20in%202015%20and%202020.%20图片：%20Maxar%20Technologies&amp;amp;type=slider&amp;amp;&quot; data-alt=&quot;Slider&quot;>; &lt;a href=&quot;https://interactive.guim.co.uk/2018/08/interactive-now-and-then-embed/embed/embed.html?mobile_before=//i .guim.co.uk/img/media/7507d0a957ed127b97ee2b761ab698fcbe134bd5/0_0_7837_6379/master/7837.jpg----宽度=2000____质量=85____s=e0b899ecf3b90cfd92075c3b51fff5ef&amp;amp;desk top_before=//i.guim.co.uk/img/media/7507d0a957ed127b97ee2b761ab698fcbe134bd5/ 0_0_7837_6379/master/7837.jpg----宽度=1000____quality=85____s=b8d1226d4924d7f1876fa7a90d0b0fcc&amp;label_before=2015&amp;amp;mobile_after=//i.guim.co.uk/img/media/7f671d724c94249a4 bf9768461c466d121f93015/0_0_7837_6379/master/7837.jpg-- --width=2000____quality=85____s=1eb1d7cbe72368869026cfd9c8c1d133&amp;amp;desktop_after=//i.guim.co.uk/img/media/7f671d724c94249a4bf9768461c466d121f93015/0_0_7837_63 79/master/7837.jpg----宽度=1000____质量=85____s=e3942edc059d1eb35162717ae493713f&amp;label_after=2020&amp;amp; ;analytics_label=Fiery%20Cross%20Reef%20part%20of%20the%20Spratly%20Islands%20group%20in%202015%20and%202020.%20Picture:%20Maxar%20Technologies&amp;amp;type=slider&amp;amp;&quot;>;互动&lt;/a>; &lt;/图>; &lt;p>;中国否认正在将这片海域军事化，称其支持和平与稳定。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;斯坦福大学研究员雷蒙德·鲍威尔表示，北京是否有进一步建造人工岛礁的计划尚不清楚美国大学国家安全创新快结中心。中国尚未开发黄岩岛，它于 2012 年占领了黄岩岛。“我们所看到的情况是，他们只是利用现有的人工地物，特别是港口，向前投射他们的力量，特别是进行更大的存在活动。”他们的海上民兵和海岸警卫队，”鲍威尔说。他补充说，船只聚集在关键地物上，或者被拴住，以建立“浮动前哨基地”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;战略与国际研究中心亚洲海事透明度倡议的研究发现，中国海岸警卫队的存在2022 年“比以往任何时候都更加强大”，并且几乎每天都在海上的关键地物进行巡逻。&lt;/p>; &lt;h2>;马尼拉迫在眉睫的困境&lt;/h2>; &lt;p>;在总统小费迪南德·马科斯 (Ferdinand Marcos Jr) 的领导下， 2022 年 6 月上台的菲律宾 &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/feb/15/philippines-president-summons-chinese-ambassador-over-laser-incident&quot;>;对中国采取了比前任政府更坚定的立场&lt;/a>;，公开谴责并分享中国所谓侵略的镜头。鲍威尔表示，今年是一个转折点，并补充说，菲律宾正在积极宣传中国的所谓“灰色地带”活动，这些活动具有胁迫性，但低于战争的门槛。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;他补充说，这有助于增强国内国防投资意愿，并有助于获得更大的国际支持。今年早些时候，菲律宾扩大了美国对其军事基地的使用范围，并加深了与日本和澳大利亚等其他国家的关系。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;菲律宾现在面临着如何维持其在南沙仁爱礁的存在的两难困境。岛屿上有一艘生锈的二战舰艇，于 1990 年代末故意搁浅于此，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/09/us-beijing-shipwreck-military -outpost-south-china-sea-philippines&quot;>;作为少数菲律宾军队的基地&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;人们担心，建造或更换该基地的尝试会引起菲律宾的反应中国也声称对该地点拥有主权，但该建筑无法在目前的状况下无限期地存在。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;美国的支持迄今为止仅限于“情报、监视和侦察 (ISR) 任务”，而菲律宾则马尼拉智库亚太进步之路研究员亚伦·杰德·拉贝纳 (Aaron Jed Rabena) 表示，轮换和重新调配任务。目前尚不清楚是否会加强这一行动。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;本周，菲律宾海岸警卫队发言人杰伊·塔里拉 (Jay Tarriela) 执行了拆除黄岩岛通道障碍任务后，告诉 CNN 菲律宾，该国“将始终如一地采取行动”。 ”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Koh 表示，他相信中国不太可能软化立场。 “但总有一天，这些灰色地带策略以及过去随之而来的成功将继续发展。那么问题是中国接下来会怎样？”&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 29 Sep 2023 10:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[California county abuzz after far-right figure appointed for mosquito control]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/28/california-shasta-county-far-right-mosquito-vaccine]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-29T01:12:29Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/ddfc32cdd36d09b40152b0ac90c5e46250338ed9/0_188_3000_1800 /master/3000.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=7b9880d82470a4567b6b962ab0ead54f&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;加州雷丁以北沙斯塔湖上的船屋。&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;自从极右运动以来在加利福尼亚州沙斯塔县获得地方政府控制权后，他们试图扔掉投票机，转而采用手工计票，并承诺使用一切“合法手段”捍卫第二修正案。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;本周他们集中精力新目标：蚊子。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/aug/14 /revealed-neo-nazi-active-club-us-military-members&quot;>;透露：新纳粹活跃俱乐部的成员中有多名美军&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;沙斯塔县监事会任命乔恩·奈特（Jon Knight）为负责管理昆虫的公共卫生机构董事会成员，他是一家水培商店老板，也是当地极右运动的知名人物，而不是该县前公共卫生主任、流行病学家。 &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;此举表明极端保守运动在地方政府中的立足点日益增强。地方政府委员会的任命通常很少引起关注，但在沙斯塔县，该县在大流行期间成为极右政治和边缘思想的温床，在最近的一次县政府会议上，这一任命成为广泛讨论的主题&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;奈特的一些支持者在会上分享了蚊子阴谋论，暗示美国官员计划强行给人们接种蚊子疫苗。 “我不相信我们的政府，”一名妇女说。 “比尔·盖茨是其中的一部分......这些蚊子将成为飞行的注射器。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;盖茨基金会资助了一项研究，尝试创造可以将疟疾疫苗输送给人类的蚊子，这些努力是边缘群体的努力试图将其描绘成一场违背人们意愿的邪恶运动。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;沙斯塔县近年来一直是争议的中心，因为该县强烈藐视新冠病毒限制措施，并因此对关注州卫生的公职人员构成威胁规则并选举强大的极右翼联盟进入该地区的最高职位。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;今年，该地区的管理机构监事会撤销了该县&lt;a href=&quot;https:/ /www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/apr/04/far-right-county- throws-out-voting-machines-with-nothing-to-replace-them&quot;>;针对谎言的投票系统&lt;/a>;关于选举舞弊。县级会议已经变成了功能失调、长达数小时的争吵，发言者受到逮捕威胁，在某些情况下，公众被勒令离开。在今年早些时候的一次会议上，一位演讲者使用了&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.sfgate.com/politics/article/shasta-county-n-word-incident-patrick-jones-18130373.php&quot;>;种族歧视诽谤&lt;/a>;，引起观众中一名男子的愤怒，该男子随后被迫离开。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;在本周的会议上，沙斯塔蚊子和病媒控制区委员会的任命问题上的紧张局势显而易见。该县前公共卫生主任唐纳尔·尤尔特 (Donnell Ewert) 曾寻求该席位，但董事会主席拒绝了他的申请。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;一些支持有关蚊子的阴谋论并对尤尔特持批评态度的居民表示支持这一任命。董事会主席帕特里克·琼斯 (Patrick Jones) 也表达了他们的一些观点。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“我会把自己的健康交给乔恩·奈特 (Jon Knight)，而不是唐纳尔·埃沃特 (Donnell Ewert)，”他说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;奈特在向董事会发表的讲话中强调了他在杀虫剂和蚊子方面的背景和知识，认为他是志愿者职位的良好候选人。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“我不知道房间里的其他人是否有销售农药已经有 18 年了，”他说。 “我对这些东西了解很多。我对比尔·盖茨的一些项目了解很多。这不是阴谋，这是事实。日本科学家发明了飞行注射器，可以为人群大规模接种疫苗。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“我们生活在一个有趣的科幻时代。凭借我对蚊子发生情况的了解以及对杀虫剂的了解，我认为我可以做得非常好。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;令一些官员和居民沮丧的是，董事会任命了奈特，他是- 创立了 Red, White and Blueprint，这是一家由极右翼活动人士创办的当地媒体公司，&lt;a href=&quot;https://anewscafe.com/2023/03/23/redding/town-hall-event-features- Supervisors-favoritism-evasion-deception/#jp-carousel-126598&quot;>;据报道&lt;/a>;于 1 月 6 日在美国国会大厦举行。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“你会忽视可能是最重要的人的申请，这几乎是可笑的投票反对这一任命的温和派玛丽·里克特 (Mary Rickert) 表示，“你知道这会让我们看起来怎么样吗？”作为一个县？这让我们看起来像白痴。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;在同一次会议上，董事会投票决定先发制人地反对任何新的新冠限制措施。&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 29 Sep 2023 09:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Stefanos Kasselakis: new leader of Greek opposition party to do military service]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/29/stefanos-kasselakis-new-leader-of-greek-opposition-party-to-do-military-service]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-28T23:27:39Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/fe71a9d14254630b331c3659b260256bda345bb1/0_80_3543_2126 /master/3543.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=7df82aa039a10112127a0b03cf3c9f80&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;激进左翼联盟领导人斯特凡诺斯·卡塞拉基斯。&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;就在当选希腊新领导人几天后左翼主要反对党斯特凡诺斯·卡塞拉基斯 (Stefanos Kasselakis) 表示，他将暂时脱离政治，参军。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;35 岁的卡塞拉基斯表示，他计划“很快”服兵役，这是强制性的对于所有希腊男人来说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;他在周四接受星空电视台采访时表示，“服兵役将是一种荣幸”。 “我很开心。一旦党的机构开会并且一切都安排妥当，我很快就会去。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;激进左翼联盟党领导人，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/ sep/24/political-outsider-stefanos-kasselakis-wins-race-to-lead-greeces-syriza&quot;>;周日当选&lt;/a>;，由于他从 14 岁起就住在美国，因此迄今为止一直免除兵役。回到希腊后，他现在必须在军队服役六个月，可以选择实际服役三周，然后用金钱换取剩余时间。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span >;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/25/stefanos-kasselakis-ex-banker-who-lit-up-greek-politics-to-lead-syriza&quot;>;斯特凡诺斯卡塞拉基斯：点燃希腊政坛领导激进左翼联盟的前银行家卡塞拉基斯是一位没有从政经验的商人，也是一名同性恋，他在周日的政党选举中出人意料地获胜。他取代了前总理亚历克西斯·齐普拉斯，后者 &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/jun/29/alexis-tsipras-step-down-syriza-leader-greece-election-rout&quot; >;在 6 月议会选举中惨败后辞职&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;他迅速崛起为激进左翼联盟的领导层，令党内许多左翼传统主义者感到不安，他们将他视为闯入者。 Further complicating his role as leader of Greece&#39;s biggest opposition party, Kasselakis is not a member of parliament.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;While it has a sizeable number of professional troops, Greece&#39;s military is still conscription-based, with service in most cases set at 12 months. It&#39;s unclear when Kasselakis will start his service, but Greek law gives him leeway until the beginning of 2024.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;He said Thursday he would like to serve in a unit near the land border with Turkey – Greece&#39;s historic regional rival – or on one of the eastern Aegean Sea islands.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 29 Sep 2023 07:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Peruvian man arrested for making more than 150 bomb threats to US schools]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/28/peruvian-bomb-threats-arrested-us-schools]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-28T20:40:43Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/ccd6301bfc86fa63abac9ef74168a49b9f502481/0_76_3888_2333/master/3888.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=7daec6ea579cd7ac8e0dbc4b246b592c&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;The side of a school bus with cordon tape that reads &quot;CRIME SCENE DO NOT CROSS&quot;.&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;A Peruvian man was arrested in Peru for sending more than 150 fake bomb threats to US schools, airports and a synagogue.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/12/peru-announces-air-security-pact-with-us-in-bid-to-stop-drug-planes&quot;>;Peru announces air security pact with US in bid to stop drug planes&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;Eddie Manuel Núñez Santos, 33, was arrested by Peruvian officials on Tuesday in Lima&lt;strong>;,&lt;/strong>; &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.justice.gov/usao-sdny/pr/peruvian-national-arrested-peru-sending-over-150-hoax-bomb-threats-schools-and-other&quot;>;according to a press release&lt;/a>; from the justice department.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;According to a complaint that was unsealed on Thursday in New York, Santos was charged with several federal crimes, including sending interstate communications threats as well as false information and hoaxes.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Santos was also charged with attempting to receive and manufacture child abuse images.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Authorities say that Santos sent several threats between 15 September and 21 September to locations in several states, including New York, Pennsylvania, Arizona and Connecticut.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“I placed multiple bombs in all of the schools from your School Districts. The bombs will blow up in a few hours. I&#39;ll gladly smile when your families are crying because of your deaths,” read one threat sent by Santos to a Pennsylvania school district.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In Pennsylvania alone, at least 1,100 schoolchildren in 20 school districts were evacuated due to false threats allegedly sent from Santos.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Santos also targeted the schools of minors from whom he attempted to obtain sexually explicit images.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Using the alias “Lucas”, Santos presented himself as a 15-year-old male and repeatedly asked minors for nude images.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;When said minors refused to send images or cut off contact with Santos, he later sent bomb threats to their schools.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“Not only did Santos allegedly email hundreds of hoax bomb threats terrorizing schools, hospitals, and houses of worship, he also perversely tried to sextort innocent teenage girls. His actions wasted limited law enforcement resources, put first responders in unnecessary danger, and victimized children,” the FBI assistant director in charge, James Smith, said in a press release.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;If found guilty, Santos faces a maximum sentence of life in prison, according to the press release.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;A court appearance date for Santos will be set at a future date, said a justice department representative to the Guardian.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 29 Sep 2023 05:52:01 +0800</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[US shutdown moves ever closer as McCarthy digs in over stopgap deal]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/28/government-shutdown-update-mccarthy-gaetz]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-28T20:33:06Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/64d3702235274a1ee270220bf73b727774041c25/0_184_5000_3002/master/5000.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=d3a49370a76535a60e0e3db75836e9f7&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;Kevin McCarthy, the House speaker, at the Capitol on Thursday. McCarthy predicted he would agree a deal despite time running out.&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;A &lt;a href=&quot;https://apnews.com/article/government-shutdown-congress-biden-trump-mccarthy-f1b06964cf549b09977677e5f70bf9ff&quot;>;government shutdown&lt;/a>; appeared all but inevitable as the House speaker, &lt;a href=&quot;https://apnews.com/hub/kevin-mccarthy&quot;>;Kevin McCarthy&lt;/a>;, dug in on Thursday, vowing he will not take up Senate legislation designed to keep the federal government fully running despite House Republicans&#39; struggle to unite around an alternative.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Congress is at an impasse just days before a disruptive federal shutdown that would halt paychecks for many of the federal government&#39;s roughly &lt;a href=&quot;https://apnews.com/article/shutdown-gop-federal-workers-congress-government-5978a4c7411eba06261d16c3aff3dfc5&quot;>;2 million employees&lt;/a>;, as well as 2 million active-duty military troops and reservists, furlough many of those workers and curtail government services.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/live/2023/sep/28/republican-debate-candidates-trump-biden-impeachment-latest&quot;>;Shutdown looms closer as Republicans accused of wasting time and fabricating impeachment evidence – live&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;But the House and Senate are pursuing different paths to avert those consequences, even though time is running out before government funding expires after midnight on Saturday.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The Senate is working toward passage of &lt;a href=&quot;https://apnews.com/article/government-shutdown-mccarthy-biden-trump-18ef8a03363d31742c5b4c5ecb23506f&quot;>;a bipartisan measure&lt;/a>; that would fund the government until 17 November as longer-term negotiations continue, while also providing $6bn for Ukraine and $6bn for US disaster relief.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The House, meanwhile, has teed up votes on four of the dozen annual spending bills that fund various agencies in hopes that would cajole enough Republicans to support a House-crafted continuing resolution that temporarily funds the government and &lt;a href=&quot;https://apnews.com/article/congress-immigration-house-republicans-border-security-0e19f7f27ef15c6edd73532c3813656a&quot;>;boosts security&lt;/a>; at the US border with Mexico. It&#39;s a long shot, but McCarthy predicted a deal.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“Put your money on me; we&#39;re going to get this done,” he said in a CNBC interview. “I think we can work through the weekend. I think we can figure this out.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Lawmakers were already weary from days of late-night negotiating. The strain was evident at McCarthy&#39;s closed-door meeting with Republicans on Thursday morning, which was marked by a tense exchange between the speaker and Florida congressman Matt Gaetz, according to those in the room.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Gaetz, who has taunted McCarthy for weeks with threats to oust him from his post, confronted the speaker about conservative online influencers being paid to post negative things about him. McCarthy shot back that he wouldn&#39;t waste his time on something like that, Gaetz told reporters as he exited the meeting.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;McCarthy&#39;s allies left the meeting fuming about Gaetz&#39;s tactics.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;With his majority splintering, McCarthy is scrambling to come up with a plan for preventing a shutdown and win Republican support. The speaker told Republicans he would reveal a Republican stopgap plan, known as a continuing resolution, or CR, on Friday, according to those in the room, while also trying to force Senate Democrats into giving some concessions.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;But with time running out, many GOP lawmakers were withholding support for a temporary measure until they had a chance to see it. Others are considering joining Democrats, without McCarthy&#39;s support, to bring forward a bill that would prevent a shutdown.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;With his ability to align his conference in doubt, McCarthy has little standing to negotiate with Senate Democrats. He has also attempted to draw Joe Biden into negotiations, but the Senate majority leader, Chuck Schumer, said Congress and the White House had already worked out top-line spending levels for next year with &lt;a href=&quot;https://apnews.com/article/joe-biden-debt-ceiling-budget-signing-f78a000d83cf85ffbaa2d08637844053&quot;>;an agreement this summer&lt;/a>; that allowed the government to continue borrowing to pay its bills.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;McCarthy was deviating from that deal and courting a shutdown by catering to Republicans who said it didn&#39;t do enough to cut spending, he said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“By focusing on the views of the radical few instead of the many, speaker McCarthy has made a shutdown far more likely,” Schumer said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://apnews.com/hub/joe-biden&quot;>;Biden&lt;/a>; also sought to apply more pressure on McCarthy, urging him to compromise with Democrats even though that could threaten his job.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“I think that the speaker is making a choice between his speakership and American interests,” Biden said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The White House, as well as the Department of Homeland Security, notified staff on Thursday to prepare for a shutdown, according to emails obtained by the Associated Press. Employees who are furloughed would have four hours on Monday to prepare their offices for the shutdown.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 29 Sep 2023 05:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Trump suing ex-MI6 officer who alleged he was ‘compromised’ by Russian security service]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/28/trump-suing-ex-mi6-officer-who-alleged-he-was-compromised-by-russian-security-service]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-28T20:45:00Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/9630bf77e8ba77daff996f767cd734e99eada3ef/0_0_2560_1536/master/2560.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=ecf19f5b2ccb609a7770ee15c14bf2f1&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;Composite image of Donald Trump and Christopher Steele&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;Donald Trump is suing a former MI6 officer and the intelligence consultancy he founded, high court records in England show.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The former US president, who is mired in lawsuits in his own country, is bringing a data protection claim against Orbis Business Intelligence and its founder Christopher Steele, who previously ran the secret intelligence service&#39;s Russia desk.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;According to a court order published on Thursday, a two-day hearing for the legal action is set to start on 16 October , the PA news agency reported.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;No other details of the case have been made available and the current frontrunner for the 2024 Republican presidential nomination is not expected to attend.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Steele was the author of the so-called Steele dossier, which included allegations that Trump had been “compromised” by Russian security service the FSB.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The dossier, which was leaked to the website BuzzFeed in 2017, also alleged that Vladimir Putin “supported and directed” an operation to “cultivate” Trump as a presidential candidate for “at least five years”. Trump denied the claims.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Steele and Orbis Business Intelligence were previously sued for libel by Russian national Aleksej Gubarev over the publication of the dossier, claiming they were legally responsible for BuzzFeed publishing the dossier. However, in a judgment in October 2020, Mr Justice Warby dismissed the claim.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Trump has been criminally indicted four times, including in a federal investigation into efforts to overturn the result of the 2020 presidential election which he lost to Joe Biden. Trump has pleaded not guilty in all four cases and has repeatedly cast litigation against him as part of a politically motivated, Democratic witch-hunt as he seeks a return to the White House.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Earlier this week the judge in his federal election meddling case, which is being brought by special counsel Jack Smith, said she will not recuse herself after the former president&#39;s requests that she step aside over claims of a perception of bias.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Judge Tanya Chutkan said she has ruled his lawyers failed to present evidence of those claims.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Last month, the judge presiding over the former US president&#39;s hush-money case, Juan Manuel Merchan, also declined to step aside after ruling that he definitely has the “ability to be fair and impartial”.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 29 Sep 2023 05:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Republicans struggle to provide proof of wrongdoing at Biden impeachment inquiry]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/28/biden-impeachment-hearing-house-republicans]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-28T21:03:58Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/548a6d45e575a99e671d388d773d0583d9f29fcc/0_344_5196_3117/master/5196.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=7fdd291187ed0f90543df6c8bd6b6a93&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;House Oversight Committee holds first hearing in the impeachment inquiry into Joe Biden.&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;Republicans struggled to put forward any evidence of wrongdoing by Joe Biden during a hearing on Thursday that&#39;s part of a newly launched impeachment inquiry.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The hearing did not go well for Republicans, who control the US House and allege Biden was connected to his son&#39;s business dealings that could have resulted in bribery and corruption. They have been investigating the matter for months and have yet to produce evidence linking the president to his son&#39;s financial affairs. They failed to do so again on Thursday. Instead, the strategy appeared to be to lay the groundwork to justify a longer fishing expedition.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/28/government-shutdown-update-mccarthy-gaetz&quot;>;US shutdown moves ever closer as McCarthy digs in over stopgap deal&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;The three Republican witnesses who testified on Thursday all conceded they did not have firsthand knowledge of any criminal activity by Biden. Two of those witnesses, Jonathan Turley, a conservative law professor, and Bruce Dubinsky, a forensic accountant, acknowledged that the information put forward so far by the committee did not amount to corruption.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“I have previously stated that, while I believe that an impeachment inquiry is warranted, I do not believe that the evidence currently meets the standard of a high crime and misdemeanor needed for an article of impeachment,” Turley &lt;a href=&quot;https://docs.house.gov/meetings/GO/GO00/20230928/116415/HHRG-118-GO00-Wstate-TurleyP-20230928.pdf&quot;>;said in prepared testimony&lt;/a>;. Still, Turley argued that there were signs of influence-peddling and that the committee should investigate further.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Republicans were reportedly caught off-guard by Turley&#39;s conclusion and an unnamed Republican aide &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.cnn.com/politics/live-news/biden-impeachment-hearing-house-oversight-09-28-23/index.html&quot;>;told CNN&lt;/a>; the hearing was an “unmitigated disaster” for the effort.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“I am not here today to even suggest that there was corruption, fraud, or any wrongdoing. In my opinion, more information needs to be gathered and assessed before I would make such an assessment,” Dubinsky, the forensic accountant said in his &lt;a href=&quot;https://oversight.house.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/Dubinsky-Written-Testimony-1.pdf&quot;>;opening statement&lt;/a>;.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Thursday&#39;s hearing, led by the House oversight committee, is titled The Basis for an Impeachment Inquiry of President Joseph R Biden Jr. The other Republican witness was Eileen O&#39;Connor, a former assistant attorney general in Department of Justice&#39;s tax division, &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.wsj.com/articles/throw-hunters-plea-in-the-trash-irs-justice-sabotage-shapley-4ae9aef0&quot;>;who wrote an op-ed in the Wall Street Journal&lt;/a>; criticizing the investigation into Hunter Biden&#39;s finances. O&#39;Connor served on Trump&#39;s 2016 transition team for the treasury department, &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2023/09/27/comer-biden-impeachment-hearing/&quot;>;the Washington Post reported&lt;/a>;.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The impeachment inquiry appears to be a thinly veiled effort to try and muddy the waters as Donald Trump, who leads the Republican primary field, faces four different criminal cases after being twice impeached.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;With little concrete evidence to work with, Republicans instead relied on Hunter Biden&#39;s business transactions and text messages to try and cast aspersions on the president. They offered no connection to Joe Biden.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“The dots are not connected. The name that&#39;s been mentioned the most often in this hearing is Hunter Biden, not President Biden,” Michael Gerhardt, the lone Democratic witness and a law professor at the University of North Carolina, said several hours into the hearing.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“The problem is when you sling mud, you have to have mud,” Representative Jared Moskowitz of Florida said at one point.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The White House essentially ignored the hearing. Instead, its press office blasted out several versions of the same statement throughout the day with a countdown until the government shuts down for lack of funding.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“There are 60 hours and 55 minutes until the government shuts down because of extreme House Republicans&#39; chaos and inability to govern. The consequences for the American people will be very damaging – from lost jobs, to troops working without pay, to jeopardizing important efforts to fight fentanyl, provide food assistance, and more. Nothing can distract from that,” one such statement read Thursday morning&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;With little substance to debate, and no fact witnesses to testify, the hearing often turned theatrical. At one point, Greg Casar, a representative of Texas, asked members to raise their hands if they thought both Hunter Biden and Donald Trump should be tried and held accountable for their actions if convicted. All of the Democrats present raised their hands, but no Republicans did.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“I think it is worse than embarrassing that Republicans won&#39;t raise their hands. They refuse to say that equal justice under the law should apply to everyone,” he said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Democrats also rebuked Republicans for moving forward with an impeachment inquiry absent a full vote from the US House authorizing it. It&#39;s &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2023/09/13/7-republicans-watch-impeaching-biden/&quot;>;not clear &lt;/a>;whether there is enough GOP support for impeachment in the House for it to survive a full vote.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;New York Democrat Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez also accused Republicans of presenting &lt;a href=&quot;https://x.com/ArthurDelaneyHP/status/1707434550136053844?s=20&quot;>;a fabricated text message&lt;/a>; between Jim and Hunter Biden – the president&#39;s brother and son, respectively – that she pointed out omitted critical context. Representative Byron Donalds of Florida displayed a selectively edited exchange between the two &lt;a href=&quot;https://x.com/ArthurDelaneyHP/status/1707434550136053844?s=20&quot;>;in the format of iMessages&lt;/a>;, which was not how the committee &lt;a href=&quot;https://gop-waysandmeans.house.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/T20-Exhibit-402-WhatsApp-Message-Example.pdf&quot;>;originally received the communication&lt;/a>;.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/sep/13/the-republicans-impeachment-inquiry-into-biden-is-laughably-cynical&quot;>;The Republicans&#39; impeachment inquiry into Biden is laughably cynical | Moira Donegan&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;In his opening statement, Representative James Comer, the Republican chairman of the House oversight committee, claimed the panel had obtained a “mountain of evidence” showing corruption.&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;69de9e3a0c0f0be12cc957c17bfd425ef25b4920&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/69de9e3a0c0f0be12cc957c17bfd425ef25b4920/0_288_8640_5184/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;James Comer, the oversight committee chairman at the House oversight committee impeachment inquiry.&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;600&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;James Comer, the oversight committee chairman at Joe Biden&#39;s impeachment inquiry.&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;Photograph: Jacquelyn Martin/AP&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;“He lied by telling the American people that there was an &#39;absolute wall&#39; between his official government duties and his personal life. Let&#39;s be clear: there was no wall. The door was wide open to those who purchased what a business associate described as &#39;the Biden Brand&#39;,” he said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;But New York Representative Daniel Goldman, a Democrat, said pointed to the fact that Republicans had declined to call Devon Archer, Hunter Biden&#39;s business partner to testify. He noted that, in an interview with the committee, Archer &lt;a href=&quot;https://oversight.house.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/Devon-Archer-Transcript.pdf&quot;>;had said&lt;/a>; Joe Biden “never discussed business with Hunter Biden and his associates, he got nothing from the businesses, and never took any official acts related to the businesses.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Republicans also rejected at least two efforts to subpoena Rudy Giuliani, a close ally of Donald Trump who was instrumental in spreading allegations of improprieties by Hunter Biden. Hunter Biden is currently suing Giuliani for the &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/26/hunter-biden-sues-rudy-giuliani-laptop-hard-drive&quot;>;“total annihilation”&lt;/a>; of his private data.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;For years, Republicans have sought to link Hunter Biden&#39;s business dealings with foreign companies to Biden. But after reviewing thousands of pages of Hunter Biden&#39;s financial records, they have yet to turn up any kind of substantial evidence, &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2023/09/27/comer-biden-impeachment-hearing/&quot;>;according to the New York Times.&lt;/a>; GOP lawmakers hope to build enough of a case of bribery and abuse of power by Biden.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The hearing comes as Republicans have struggled to pass a spending plan to keep the US government open. Democrats have seized on the Thursday hearing to accuse Republicans of being unserious about passing a spending plan.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Jason Smith, a Missouri Republican who chairs the House ways and means committee, also said Biden was connected to his son&#39;s business dealings, something Republicans have been unable to prove. “Whether it was lunches, phone calls, White House meetings or official foreign trips, Hunter Biden cashed in by arranging access to Joe Biden, the family brand,” Smith said in his opening remarks.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In a lengthy response, Representative Jamie Raskin, the ranking Democrat on the committee, blasted Republicans for focusing on impeachment days before the US government was set to shut down due to lack of funding.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“We&#39;re 62 hours away from shutting down the government of the United States of America and Republicans are launching an impeachment drive based on a long debunked and discredited lie,” he said. “They don&#39;t have the votes because dozens of Republicans recognize what a futile and absurd process this is.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Republicans &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.cnn.com/2023/09/26/politics/impeachment-inquiry-shutdown/index.html&quot;>;have said they will move forward with impeachment&lt;/a>;, even if the government shuts down.&lt;/p>;&lt;br>;&lt;hr>;&lt;div>;获取更多RSS：&lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.net&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.best&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.best&lt;/a>;&lt;br>;&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 29 Sep 2023 05:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s manipulation of media threatens global freedoms, says US report]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/28/chinas-manipulation-of-media-threatens-global-freedoms-says-us-report]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-28T19:53:22Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/c801081bb71c3b2b6f26e47b8a20ebb997da74c8/0_0_2500_1500/master/2500.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=7446665e39ca4ddbe1af86ccc06dd86f&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;The front pages of The Global Times and China Daily&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;China is manipulating global media through censorship, data harvesting and covert purchases of foreign news outlets, according to a new report from the US state department, which warned the trend could lead to a “sharp contraction” of global freedom of expression.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The report released on Thursday found that Beijing has spent billions of dollars annually on information manipulation efforts, including by acquiring stakes in foreign media through “public and non-public means,” sponsoring online influencers and securing distribution agreements that promote unlabelled Chinese government content.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/12/chinese-state-media-censors-itself-poem-corruption-hangzhou&quot;>;Chinese state media censors itself after highlighting poem about corrupt leaders&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;The Chinese embassy in Washington did not immediately respond to a request for comment. In July, Beijing responded to a Nato communique accusing it of coercive policies and spreading disinformation by saying the statement disregarded basic facts, deliberately discredited China and distorted its policies.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The US report comes amid controversy over China&#39;s efforts in recent years to expand the global footprint of its government-controlled media, especially as geopolitical competition between Beijing and Washington has intensified. Chinese leaders have sought to combat the negative images of China they feel are spread by world media.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Citing public reports and “newly acquired government information,” the state department&#39;s global engagement center said that Beijing had created its own information ecosystem by co-opting foreign political elites and journalists. It had also invested in satellite networks and digital television services in developing regions that prioritise Chinese state-backed media content.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/dec/07/china-plan-for-global-media-dominance-propaganda-xi-jinping&quot;>;Inside China&#39;s audacious global propaganda campaign&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;Chinese data harvesting overseas “has enabled Beijing to fine-tune global censorship by targeting specific individuals and organizations”, it said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“Unchecked, Beijing&#39;s efforts could result in ... a sharp contraction of global freedom of expression,” the report said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Despite unprecedented resources devoted to the campaign, Beijing had encountered “major setbacks” when targeting democratic countries due to local media and civil society pushback, according to the report, which was produced under a congressional mandate to detail state information manipulation.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 29 Sep 2023 04:22:01 +0800</pubDate></item></channel></rss>